      Dress codes
   =20
 =20
The pandemic has had an obvious effect on the level of formality in the fin=
ancial industry, and here is a New York Times photo feature on what people =
are wearing to their financial jobs in New York these days. Honestly it=E2=
=80=99s mostly what they would have worn two years ago:=C2=A0standard busin=
ess casual mixed with some suits and dresses; one picture, of New York in s=
ummer, features a JPMorgan-branded fleece vest. But there are sneakers and =
polo shirts here and there. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m wearing sneakers right now=
, and people are wearing jeans with blazers or shirts,=E2=80=9D says one Go=
ldman Sachs Group Inc. legal analyst.=C2=A0=C2=A0However! A weird fact of m=
edia culture is that every time the financial industry relaxes its dress co=
de, this is described as =E2=80=9CWall Street firms are ditching suits.=E2=
=80=9D This cannot keep being true. If you relax your dress code from suits=
 to business casual, and then you relax your dress code again, you are not=
=C2=A0again=C2=A0getting rid of suits. You are moving from business casual =
to jeans and polos or whatever. And so most of Wall Street =E2=80=94=C2=A0c=
ertainly including Goldman Sachs =E2=80=94=C2=A0moved to business casual du=
ring or shortly after the late-=E2=80=9990s tech boom, and so for the last =
few decades most Goldman employees have not worn suits to the office most o=
f the time.And then, in 2019, Goldman Chief Executive Officer David Solomon=
 sent out a  somewhat inscrutable memo that was widely interpreted to mean =
=E2=80=9Cyou can wear jeans sometimes.=E2=80=9D Fine, right, makes sense; w=
e are in the middle of another, even more casually dressed tech boom, and t=
o compete for developers Goldman has to move from wool pants to jeans. But =
the rules of media coverage of bank dress codes required that everyone pret=
end that Goldman now, in 2019, was finally allowing its employees to abando=
n suits and ties. =E2=80=9CGoldman Sachs Allows Bankers to Trade Bespoke Su=
its for Khakis,=E2=80=9D was  the Bloomberg headline, suggesting that befor=
e March 2019 Goldman required not only suits but=C2=A0bespoke=C2=A0suits.[6=
] Disclosure, I worked at Goldman from 2007 to 2011. Sometimes I wore a sui=
t, mainly to client meetings or when I just wanted to feel fancy. Once I wo=
re jeans? Mostly I wore business casual, like almost everyone else.But now =
that Times feature, which was published yesterday, says:Despite periodic ef=
forts to relax dress codes =E2=80=94 including in 2019, when Goldman made s=
uits and ties optional =E2=80=94 banking had been one of the last bastions =
of formal work wear, alongside law firms.That last part is=C2=A0true! It ha=
d been one of the last bastions of formal work wear! Last century!I know th=
at I have belabored this ridiculously, but I feel like we are at a tipping =
point where, if people keep writing this, in like a year or two it will no =
longer be possible to push back. It will just become retroactively true, an=
d I will have to go back and edit my memories to conform with the new share=
d reality. =E2=80=9CWow it's weird that I had to wear a suit every day when=
 I worked at Goldman,=E2=80=9D I will think, because who am I to argue with=
 what everyone else remembers.
