10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Friendly audit</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way that high-level professional=
=C2=A0services =E2=80=94=C2=A0investment banking, law, consulting, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0work=C2=A0is that a professional=C2=A0firm provides services to=
 a client company, and the company pays the firm, but particular people at =
the firm pitch and work with=C2=A0particular people at the company, and the=
 people at the company want to work with people they like and trust. And so=
 the business of a senior investment banker consists largely of winning the=
 trust and friendship of executives at companies in her coverage industry. =
Sure sometimes she will pitch a company she barely knows=C2=A0on a particul=
ar deal and win the business (or not) based on the quality of ideas in her =
pitch; other times a company will want to do a deal, will ask banks for fee=
 proposals, and will choose her if she proposes the lowest fee. But in the =
course of a career these things tend to be less important than the day-to-d=
ay building of reputation and relationships. Mostly companies will hire her=
 because their executives have worked with her before and like and trust he=
r.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are obvious, mostly low-grad=
e conflicts of interest here. Probably some banking business can be done we=
ll enough by anyone, some other bank would do it cheap, and the company ove=
rpays for it because the chief financial officer wants to work with a parti=
cular banker whom he likes and trusts. Or the chief executive officer hires=
 a banker who tells her what she wants to hear (=E2=80=9Cdo a big merger=E2=
=80=9D) rather than what is actually in the best interests of her company; =
the shareholders end up worse off because the CEO picks advisers based on p=
ersonal preference. Or of course professional service providers=C2=A0tend t=
o buy a lot of dinners and sports tickets for client executives, and while =
the clients probably mostly don=E2=80=99t hire firms based on that sort of =
everyday bribery, it=E2=80=99s a thing you could worry about.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine trying to stamp out all of these con=
flicts of interest, and in some organizations (for instance, many governmen=
ts) and some contexts people do. You set up objective criteria for hiring p=
rofessional advisers, you demand written price quotes and choose the lowest=
 one, you have some independent committee choose=C2=A0advisers on impersona=
l metrics without regard for the preferences of the executives who will wor=
k with the advisers. But mostly that is sort of silly; the actual service t=
hat these firms provide is basically =E2=80=9Cwise trusted advice,=E2=80=9D=
 and to provide that service you really do need some relationship of person=
al trust. You can=E2=80=99t just put it out to the lowest bidder.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Accounting is an unusual professional-services busin=
ess because a lot of what accounting firms do =E2=80=94=C2=A0tax and struct=
uring advice, consulting, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is very much in this vein of =
wise trusted advice, but one core function of accounting firms =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0public-company auditing =E2=80=94=C2=A0is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0only partly lik=
e that. Public-company executives do, to some extent, think of their audito=
rs as =E2=80=9Cthe people I call with accounting questions,=E2=80=9D and th=
ey want to hire auditors whom they like and trust and who they think have g=
ood judgment and good bedside manner. But auditors are also in a somewhat a=
dversarial position to their client companies, or rather to the clients=E2=
=80=99 executives: Their job is to=C2=A0<em>audit=C2=A0</em>the clients=E2=
=80=99 accounts, to check them for mistakes, to flag problems, to certify t=
o the market that the accounts have been reviewed independently and found t=
o be acceptable. If the auditors are best friends and trusted advisers to t=
he executives, then they can=E2=80=99t be independent, and the market can=
=E2=80=99t trust their audit results.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>And so you get sort of a=C2=A0weird dynamic where there are=C2=A0rules des=
igned to prevent auditors from becoming too chummy with their clients=E2=80=
=99 executives, but of course the client executives want auditors who are c=
hummy with them so they can have a pleasant audit experience, and of course=
 the auditors want to be chummy with client executives so they can keep and=
 win business.[1] And occasionally you get weird Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission enforcement actions <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/24637902.261044/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVh=
c2UvMjAyMS0xNDQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ff3470c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">like this one</a>:</p><blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission [yester=
day] charged accounting firm Ernst &amp; Young LLP (EY), one of its partner=
s, and two of its former partners with improper professional conduct for vi=
olating auditor independence rules in connection with EY's pursuit to serve=
 as the independent auditor for a public company with nearly $5 billion in =
revenue (issuer). Separately, the Commission brought charges against the Is=
suer's then-Chief Accounting Officer for his role in the misconduct. All re=
spondents have agreed to settle the charges and will collectively pay more =
than $10 million in monetary relief.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SE=
C's order against the auditors finds that EY, EY partner James Herring, CPA=
, and former EY partners, James Young, CPA and Curt Fochtmann, CPA improper=
ly interfered with the issuer's selection of an independent auditor by soli=
citing and receiving confidential competitive intelligence and confidential=
 audit committee information from the issuer's then-Chief Accounting Office=
r, William Stiehl, during the request for proposal process. EY's misconduct=
 in connection with the audit pursuit, the order finds, would cause a reaso=
nable investor to conclude that EY and its partners were incapable of exerc=
ising objectivity and impartiality once the audit engagement began. The SEC=
's separate order against Stiehl finds that, through his misconduct during =
the request for proposal process, including withholding key information fro=
m the issuer's audit committee, Stiehl caused the issuer's reporting violat=
ions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"Auditor independence is not merely a=
n obstacle to overcome, it is the bedrock foundation that supports the inte=
grity, transparency, and reliability of financial reporting," said Charles =
Cain, Chief of the SEC Enforcement Division's FCPA Unit. "Auditor independe=
nce requires auditors to analyze all of the relevant facts and circumstance=
s from the perspective of the reasonable investor. EY and its partners lost=
 sight of this fundamental principle in their pursuit of a new client. This=
 action further underscores that auditors must apply heightened scrutiny wh=
en making independence determinations."</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The background here is that, from 2004 to 2012, Stiehl =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the corporate accounting executive =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cserved in =
internal audit and senior<br />financial roles for two public companies=E2=
=80=9D that were audited by EY and where Herring was the audit partner.[2] =
=E2=80=9CDuring those eight years, Stiehl and [Herring] worked closely toge=
ther, and Stiehl came to view [Herring] as a trusted advisor.=E2=80=9D Righ=
t, yes, as a provider of professional services, you want to be viewed as a =
trusted adviser to the client executives you work with; as a corporate exec=
utive, you want to have professional service providers whom you can trust f=
or advice.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then Stiehl moved on to be the c=
hief accounting officer at=C2=A0another company; the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t na=
me it but it=E2=80=99s Sealed Air Corp.[3] =E2=80=9CAt the time, another ac=
counting firm had served as Issuer=E2=80=99s independent auditor for decade=
s.=E2=80=9D (It was KPMG LLP.) But in February 2013, a month after Stiehl j=
oined, Sealed Air started planning a request-for-proposal (RFP) process to =
consider hiring a new auditor.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And there wa=
s that conflict. On the one hand, the audit committee of Sealed Air=E2=80=
=99s board wanted to do a good process to get the best possible audit at th=
e lowest possible price. The audit committee is made up of independent dire=
ctors, they have duties=C2=A0to the shareholders, they are responsible for =
making sure the accounts are right, they want to get a good and independent=
 audit, all that good stuff:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On=
 July 14, 2014, after Issuer=E2=80=99s Audit Committee authorized the RFP=
=E2=80=99s requirements and rules, Issuer invited EY and three other audit =
firms, including Issuer=E2=80=99s then-incumbent audit firm, to submit bids=
 in what the Audit Committee intended to be a competitive and fair RFP proc=
ess. The RFP documents stated that Issuer intended that the process would a=
llow all prospective =E2=80=9CIndependent Registered Public Accounting Firm=
[s]=E2=80=9D an =E2=80=9Cequal opportunity to provide their best proposals=
=E2=80=9D to Issuer=E2=80=99s Audit Committee.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand Stiehl, the chief accounting officer, wh=
o was responsible for doing the accounts and who would spend the most time =
with the auditor, wanted that auditor to be someone he liked and trusted an=
d worked well with. Specifically he wanted it to be his old buddy Herring. =
So:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Issuer worked internally=
 to initiate the RFP process, Stiehl began to provide certain confidential =
information to [Herring]. In August 2013, without Issuer=E2=80=99s knowledg=
e, Stiehl provided Audit Partner and [EY] with a draft RFP presentation to =
Issuer=E2=80=99s Audit Committee. Stiehl did not provide this pre-RFP confi=
dential information to any other audit firm. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Stiehl allowed =
[EY] to assist in drafting portions of Issuer=E2=80=99s RFP before it=C2=A0=
was publicly released and arranged for [Herring] to meet with Stiehl=E2=80=
=99s financial personnel at least a month before other firms=E2=80=99 perso=
nnel were invited to do so.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An=
d then, when the proposals started coming in, EY very much had the inside t=
rack:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stiehl also gave [EY] an =
open invitation to provide suggestions or comments to RFP materials summari=
zing each competitors=E2=80=99 proposals that were going to the Audit Commi=
ttee. On multiple occasions during the RFP process, [EY] solicited and rece=
ived information from Stiehl outside of the RFP=E2=80=99s data room, includ=
ing =E2=80=9Cintegral=E2=80=9D incumbent fee information, which enabled [EY=
] =E2=80=9Cto come up with an informed fee for the RFP.=E2=80=9D</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stiehl unilaterally shared intelligence with [EY] bec=
ause he wanted [EY] to =E2=80=9Cget a seat at the table in the ultimate RFP=
.=E2=80=9D Stiehl did not act with the Audit Committee=E2=80=99s authority =
or with the knowledge or approval of Issuer=E2=80=99s senior management.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">EY even got the opportunit=
y to trash-talk its competitors in Stiehl=E2=80=99s board=C2=A0materials[4]=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, on October 3, 20=
14, Stiehl sent [EY], through [Herring], =E2=80=9Cthe slide deck that I pla=
n to share in executive committee,=E2=80=9D and asked [Herring] to share =
=E2=80=9Cadditional talking points that you think might be beneficial=E2=80=
=9D before Stiehl met with the Audit Committee to present his views of the =
competing firms. Stiehl was not authorized or instructed to share this info=
rmation with [EY] or to solicit additional talking points. Stiehl did not t=
ell anyone within Issuer that he had done so. Stiehl=E2=80=99s 16-page slid=
e deck identified each competing audit firm by =E2=80=9CKey Qualitative Hig=
hlights,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CPros and Cons,=E2=80=9D and bid amount. Three da=
ys later, on October 6, 2014, [Herring] provided Stiehl with a detailed lis=
t of additional =E2=80=9CCons=E2=80=9D against the incumbent audit firm, in=
cluding one that [Herring] stated was a =E2=80=9Cbig negative the [Audit Co=
mmittee] would be interested in=E2=80=9D and additional =E2=80=9CPros=E2=80=
=9D in favor of [EY], including one that [Herring] urged =E2=80=9Cmaybe you=
 [Stiehl] could play that up=E2=80=9D prior to the Audit Committee=E2=80=99=
s scheduled down-selection meeting on October 7, 2014.=C2=A0</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thing is, this is just exactly where you=
 want to be as a provider of professional services. If you are an investmen=
t banker and the CFO of a company calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey we are=
 soliciting proposals for our IPO, I want you to lead it, could you send me=
 some talking points about why your competitors are garbage,=E2=80=9D you h=
ave done your job exactly right. You have won the trust and loyalty of a se=
nior decision-maker=C2=A0at an important client, you are doing the things =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0making his life easier, helping him with board materials, ma=
king him look good in front of his bosses =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you are taugh=
t to do for your clients, and it is winning you lucrative business. Just=C2=
=A0A+ work.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In auditing this analysis is no=
t quite right, but the same instinct is there. EY got the business, and glo=
ated internally about how it got it:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">An internal EY victory =E2=80=98case study=E2=80=99 prepared shortly =
after EY was awarded the Issuer audit described this access as a =E2=80=9Ch=
ead start none of the=C2=A0other firms were given.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, building trusted relationships with publ=
ic-company executives is how you do the business.[5] Except sometimes not. =
Also here=E2=80=99s another good gloat:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The Audit Committee unanimously selected and appointed EY as Issue=
r=E2=80=99s new auditor. In an email to EY=E2=80=99s national leadership, E=
Y Partners characterized the appointment as a =E2=80=9C$10 million a year a=
nnuity which will span across multiple service lines.=E2=80=9D That night, =
[Stiehl] sent another EY partner ([Stiehl=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0former college ro=
ommate), a congratulatory email with the message: =E2=80=9CBack in the fami=
ly!!!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A good wa=
y to win professional-services business is by having been college roommates=
 with the key decision-makers.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">People are worried about GAAP accounting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have an occasional recurring segment=
 around here called =E2=80=9Cpeople are worried about non-GAAP accounting,=
=E2=80=9D where I quote someone fretting that some company has disclosed nu=
mbers that do not conform to U.S. generally accepted accounting principles,=
 and calling those numbers =E2=80=9Cfake=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cimaginary=E2=
=80=9D or whatever. I am not generally moved by these worries. Every compan=
y that discloses non-GAAP numbers also has to disclose the GAAP ones; if in=
vestors do not believe in non-GAAP numbers they can ignore them. But compan=
ies like to disclose non-GAAP numbers because they think that the GAAP ones=
 do not reflect reality in some important way; GAAP is a set of standardize=
d conventions, but sometimes it can distort economic reality. That or the c=
ompanies just like that the non-GAAP numbers are usually higher.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is an article <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24637902.261044/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMzAvbWljcm9zdHJhdGVneS1iaXRjb2luLWJldC1p=
cy1hLXdpbi1hbmQtYS1sb3NzLWF0LXRoZS1zYW1lLXRpbWU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc6=
ac0053" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a=
bout MicroStrategy Inc.</a>, which is sort of a software company but mostly=
 a big pot of Bitcoins. When the price of Bitcoin goes up, the economic val=
ue of MicroStrategy goes up; when the price of Bitcoin goes down, the econo=
mic value of MicroStrategy goes down. But GAAP accounting for Bitcoin proud=
ly ignores this economic reality: Under GAAP, when Bitcoin goes down, compa=
nies that hold Bitcoin have to write it down (and take a loss on their inco=
me statements), but when it goes up they don=E2=80=99t write it up or book =
any profit.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so in the real world =
of money, MicroStrategy has made a lot of money on Bitcoin, but in the styl=
ized world of GAAP, it has lost a lot of money on Bitcoin:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The tech company=E2=80=99s 105,085 Bitcoin woul=
d produce a paper gain of about $1.4 billion if sold at Friday=E2=80=99s pr=
ices -- that=E2=80=99s more than double what MicroStrategy has posted in cu=
mulative earnings in the last 25 years, data compiled by Bloomberg show. Th=
at nominal gain is also more than three-times the revenue generated by the =
company since it adopted Bitcoin as its primary treasury asset last August.=
 ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MicroStrategy had roughly 105,085 Bitc=
oins as of June 30, at an average cost of $26,080 compared to Friday=E2=80=
=99s level of $39,050, the report showed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">B=
itcoin holdings come at a cost though. The company disclosed in its quarter=
ly statement cumulative impairment losses of $689.6 million related to the =
digital asset.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MicroStrategy=
=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2463790=
2.261044/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMT=
A1MDQ0Ni8wMDAxNTY0NTkwMjEwMzkxMjUvbXN0ci0xMHFfMjAyMTA2MzAuaHRt/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB18a3a949" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">10-Q says</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As =
of June 30, 2021, the carrying value of the Company=E2=80=99s approximately=
 105,085 bitcoins was $2.051 billion, which reflects cumulative impairments=
 of $689.6 million. As of December 31, 2020, the carrying value of the Comp=
any=E2=80=99s approximately 70,469 bitcoins was $1.054 billion, which refle=
cted cumulative impairments of $70.7 million.=C2=A0The carrying value repre=
sents the lowest fair value (based on Level 1 inputs in the fair value hier=
archy) of the bitcoins at any time since their acquisition. Therefore, thes=
e fair value measurements were made during the period from their acquisitio=
n through June 30, 2021 or December 31, 2020, respectively, and not as of J=
une 30, 2021 or December 31, 2020, respectively.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might think that it would be helpful for investors=
 if MicroStrategy said things like =E2=80=9Cwe have $4.1 billion worth of B=
itcoins, which we bought for $2.7 billion, meaning that we=E2=80=99re up $1=
.4 billion.=E2=80=9D That would be helpful because it is true. Instead it h=
as to say things like =E2=80=9Cwe have $2.05 billion worth of Bitcoins, whi=
ch we bought for $2.7 billion, meaning that we=E2=80=99re down $700 million=
,=E2=80=9D and throw a bunch of asterisks on that because it is not true. I=
t is, however, correct under generally accepted accounting principles, and =
if MicroStrategy said the true thing instead then it would get criticized f=
or its non-GAAP accounting.</p>
