</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pandemic has had an obvious effect=
 on the level of formality in the financial industry, and here is a <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24637902.261044/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8wOC8wMi9idXNpbmVzcy93YWxsLXN0cmVldC1jYXN1YWwu=
aHRtbD9yZWZlcnJpbmdTb3VyY2U9YXJ0aWNsZVNoYXJl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcc1b5=
eea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">New Y=
ork Times photo feature</a> on what people are wearing to their financial j=
obs in New York these days. Honestly it=E2=80=99s mostly what they would ha=
ve worn two years ago:=C2=A0standard business casual mixed with some suits =
and dresses; one picture, of New York in summer, features a JPMorgan-brande=
d fleece vest. But there are sneakers and polo shirts here and there. =E2=
=80=9CI=E2=80=99m wearing sneakers right now, and people are wearing jeans =
with blazers or shirts,=E2=80=9D says one Goldman Sachs Group Inc. legal an=
alyst.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However! A weird fact of=
 media culture is that every time the financial industry relaxes its dress =
code, this is described as =E2=80=9CWall Street firms are ditching suits.=
=E2=80=9D This cannot keep being true. If you relax your dress code from su=
its to business casual, and then you relax your dress code again, you are n=
ot=C2=A0<em>again=C2=A0</em>getting rid of suits. You are moving from busin=
ess casual to jeans and polos or whatever. And so most of Wall Street =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0certainly including Goldman Sachs =E2=80=94=C2=A0moved to busin=
ess casual during or shortly after the late-=E2=80=9990s tech boom, and so =
for the last few decades most Goldman employees have not worn suits to the =
office most of the time.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then, in 2019,=
 Goldman Chief Executive Officer David Solomon sent out a <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24637902.261044/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMDYvYmUtY2FyZWZ1bC13ZWFyaW=
5nLWplYW5zLWF0LWdvbGRtYW4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa36ffa9c" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> somewhat inscrutable me=
mo</a> that was widely interpreted to mean =E2=80=9Cyou can wear jeans some=
times.=E2=80=9D Fine, right, makes sense; we are in the middle of another, =
even more casually dressed tech boom, and to compete for developers Goldman=
 has to move from wool pants to jeans. But the rules of media coverage of b=
ank dress codes required that everyone pretend that Goldman now, in 2019, w=
as finally allowing its employees to abandon suits and ties. =E2=80=9CGoldm=
an Sachs Allows Bankers to Trade Bespoke Suits for Khakis,=E2=80=9D was <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24637902.261044/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMDUvZ29sZG1hbi1z=
YWNocy1hbGxvd3MtYmFua2Vycy10by10cmFkZS1iZXNwb2tlLXN1aXRzLWZvci1raGFraXM/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e1cdfca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> the Bloomberg headline</a>, suggesting that before M=
arch 2019 Goldman required not only suits but=C2=A0<em>bespoke=C2=A0</em>su=
its.[6] Disclosure, I worked at Goldman from 2007 to 2011. Sometimes I wore=
 a suit, mainly to client meetings or when I just wanted to feel fancy. Onc=
e I wore jeans? Mostly I wore business casual, like almost everyone else.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now that Times feature, which was publis=
hed yesterday, says:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite pe=
riodic efforts to relax dress codes =E2=80=94 including in 2019, when Goldm=
an made suits and ties optional =E2=80=94 banking had been one of the last =
bastions of formal work wear, alongside law firms.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That last part is=C2=A0true! It <em>had</em> been one =
of the last bastions of formal work wear! Last century!</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">I know that I have belabored this ridiculously, but I feel lik=
e we are at a tipping point where, if people keep writing this, in like a y=
ear or two it will no longer be possible to push back. It will just become =
retroactively true, and I will have to go back and edit my memories to conf=
orm with the new shared reality. =E2=80=9CWow it's weird that I had to wear=
 a suit every day when I worked at Goldman,=E2=80=9D I will think, because =
who am I to argue with what everyone else remembers.</p><table class=3D"hea=
der" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
